:00 <includeonly>[[Time in Argentina|ART]]</includeonly>\n|team1      = {{fb-rt|AUS}}\n|score      = {{score link|2021 Copa Am\u00e9rica Group A#Australia vs Bolivia|Match 16}}\n|team2      = {{fb|BOL}}\n|goals1     =\n|goals2     =\n|stadium    = [[Estadio Ciudad de La Plata]], [[La Plata]]\n|attendance =\n|referee    =\n|report     =\n}}<section end=A09 />\n\n===Matchday 4===\n\n====Chile vs Paraguay====\n<section begin=A10 />{{Football box\n|date       = {{Start date|2020|6|25|df=y}}\n|time       = 20:00 <includeonly>[[Time in Argentina|ART]]</includeonly>\n|team1      = {{fb-rt|CHI}}\n|score      = {{score link|2021 Copa Am\u00e9rica Group A#Chile vs Paraguay|Match 19}}\n|team2      = {{fb|PAR}}\n|goals1     =\n|goals2     =\n|stadium    = [[Estadio Mario Alberto Kempes]], [[C\u00f3rdoba, Argentina|C\u00f3rdoba]]\n|attendance =\n|referee    =\n|report     =\n}}<section end=A10 />\n\n====Bolivia vs Uruguay====\n<section begin=A11 />{{Football box\n|date       = {{Start date|2020|6|26|df=y}}\n|time       = 19:00 <includeonly>[[Time in Argentina|ART]]</includeonly>\n|team1      = {{fb-rt|BOL}}\n|score      = {{score link|2021 Copa Am\u00e9rica Group A#Bolivia vs Uruguay|Match 21}}\n|team2      = {{fb|URU}}\n|goals1     =\n|goals2     =\n|stadium    = [[Estadio Ciudad de La Plata]], [[La Plata]]\n|attendance =\n|referee    =\n|report     =\n}}<section end=A11 />\n\n====Australia vs Argentina====\n<section begin=A12 />{{Football box\n|date       = {{Start date|2020|6|26|df=y}}\n|time       = 22:00 <includeonly>[[Time in Argentina|ART]]</includeonly>\n|team1      = {{fb-rt|AUS}}\n|score      = {{score link|2021 Copa Am\u00e9rica Group A#Australia vs Argentina|Match 20}}\n|team2      = {{fb|ARG}}\n|goals1     =\n|goals2     =\n|stadium    = [[Estadio Monumental Antonio Vespucio Liberti|Estadio Monumental]], [[Buenos Aires]]\n|attendance =\n|referee    =\n|report     =\n}}<section end=A12 />\n\n===Matchday 5===\n\n====Chile vs Australia====\n<section begin=A13 />{{Football box\n|date       = {{Start date|2020|6|30|df=y}}\n|time       = 20:00 <includeonly>[[Time in Argentina|ART]]</includeonly>\n|team1      = {{fb-rt|CHI}}\n|score      = {{score link|2021 Copa Am\u00e9rica Group A#Chile vs Australia|Match 25}}\n|team2      = {{fb|AUS}}\n|goals1     =\n|goals2     =\n|stadium    = [[Estadio Mario Alberto Kempes]], [[C\u00f3rdoba, Argentina|C\u00f3rdoba]]\n|attendance =\n|referee    =\n|report     =\n}}<section end=A13 />\n\n====Bolivia vs Argentina====\n<section begin=A14 />{{Football box\n|date       = {{Start date|2020|6|30|df=y}}\n|time       = 20:00 <includeonly>[[Time in Argentina|ART]]</includeonly>\n|team1      = {{fb-rt|BOL}}\n|score      = {{score link|2021 Copa Am\u00e9rica Group A#Bolivia vs Argentina|Match 26}}\n|team2      = {{fb|ARG}}\n|goals1     =\n|goals2     =\n|stadium    = [[Estadio Ciudad de La Plata]], [[La Plata]]\n|attendance =\n|referee    =\n|report     =\n}}<section end=A14 />\n\n====Uruguay vs Paraguay====\n<section begin=A15 />{{Football box\n|date       = {{Start date|2020|6|30|df=y}}\n|time       = 20:00 <includeonly>[[Time in Argentina|ART]]</includeonly>\n|team1      = {{fb-rt|URU}}\n|score      = {{score link|2021 Copa Am\u00e9rica Group A#Uruguay vs Paraguay|Match 27}}\n|team2      = {{fb|PAR}}\n|goals1     =\n|goals2     =\n|stadium    = [[Estadio \u00danico de Santiago del Estero|Estadio \u00danico]], [[Santiago del Estero]]\n|attendance =\n|referee    =\n|report     =\n}}<section end=A15 />\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Official website|http://copaamerica.com}}\n\n{{2021 Copa Am\u00e9rica}}\n\n[[Category:2021 Copa Am\u00e9rica|Group A]]\n", "name_user": "S.A. Julio", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eTeams:fix", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2021_Copa_Am%C3%A9rica_Group_A"}
{"title_page": "Cuomo family", "text_new": "{{about|the New York political family|other uses|Cuomo (disambiguation)}}\n[[File:Andrew_Cuomo_2014.jpg|250px|thumb|upright|[[Andrew Cuomo]], [[governor of New York]]]]\nThe '''Cuomo family''' ({{IPAc-en|\u02c8|k|w|o\u028a|m|o\u028a}} {{respell|KWOH|moh}}, {{IPA-it|\u02c8kw\u0254\u02d0mo|lang}}) is an [[United States|American]] [[political family]]. It includes [[Mario Cuomo|Mario]] and [[Matilda Cuomo]] (''n\u00e9e'' Raffa) and their five children: [[Margaret I. Cuomo|Margaret]], [[Andrew Cuomo|Andrew]], Maria, Madeline, and [[Chris Cuomo|Christopher]]. [[Mario Cuomo]] and his son [[Andrew Cuomo]] both have served as [[governor of New York]].\n\nMario Cuomo's parents, Andrea and Immacolata Cuomo, both [[immigration to the United States|immigrated to the United States]] from Italy; Andrea in 1926 and Immacolata in 1927.<ref>\"[https://www.nytimes.com/1995/04/25/obituaries/immaculata-cuomo-92-governor-s-mother.html Immaculata Cuomo, 92, Governor's Mother]\" (April 25, 1995), ''New York Times''.</ref> Matilda Raffa Cuomo's parents both immigrated to the United State from Sicily; Carmelo \"Charles\" Raffa arrived in New York in 1927, and Mary ([[Birth name|n\u00e9e]] Gitto) Raffa in 1928.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1995/06/23/obituaries/mary-raffa-cuomo-s-mother-in-law-91.html|title=Mary Raffa; Cuomo's Mother-in-Law, 91|date=1995-06-23|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-03-30|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>\n*[[Mario Cuomo]] (June 15, 1932 \u2013 January 1, 2015), unsuccessful candidate for [[Lieutenant Governor of New York]] (1974); appointed [[New York Secretary of State]] by Governor [[Hugh Carey]] (1975\u20131978); unsuccessful candidate in 1977 Democratic primary for [[mayor of New York City]] (lost to [[Ed Koch]]); unsuccessful [[Liberal Party of New York]] candidate in general election for mayor of New York City (1977), again losing to Ed Koch; Lieutenant Governor of New York 1979\u20131982; [[Governor of New York]] (1983\u20131994); keynote speaker at the [[1984 Democratic National Convention]] in [[San Francisco]].<ref>http://www.italian-american.com/mario-cu.htm</ref>\n*[[Matilda Cuomo]], (born September 16, 1931) former First Lady of New York (1983\u20131994); educator and lifelong advocate for women, children, and families; proponent of New York State Mentoring Program; founder of Mentoring USA nonprofit organization; inducted into [[National Women's Hall of Fame]] in 2017.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.timesunion.com/tuplus-local/article/Matilda-Cuomo-thrilled-by-National-Women-s-Hall-10926137.php|title=Matilda Cuomo thrilled by National Women's Hall of Fame induction|last=Grondahl|first=Paul|date=2017-02-12|website=Times Union|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-05}}</ref>\n*[[Margaret I. Cuomo|Margaret Cuomo]] (born March 29, 1955) daughter of Matilda and Mario Cuomo, is a noted physician and radiologist; author and champion of cancer prevention; co-founder of the Italian Language Foundation.\n*[[Andrew Cuomo]] (born December 6, 1957), son of Mario and Matilda Cuomo; [[United States Secretary of Housing and Urban Development]] (1997\u20132001); [[New York State Attorney General]] (2007\u20132010); [[governor of New York]] (2011\u2013present).<ref>{{cite news| url=http://findarticles.com/p/articles/mi_m1571/is_n11_V9/ai_13625807 | work=Insight on the News | first=Kenneth | last=Silber | title=New testing ground for the other Cuomo - Andrew Cuomo, son of New York State Governor Mario Cuomo | date=March 15, 1993}}</ref> From 1990 to 2003, Andrew Cuomo was married to [[Kerry Kennedy]], daughter of [[Robert F. Kennedy]] and [[Ethel Skakel]].<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20121023042328/http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P1-75020276.html HighBeam]</ref> After Cuomo and Kennedy divorced, Cuomo dated Food Network host [[Sandra Lee (cook)|Sandra Lee]] from 2005 until September 2019.<ref>{{cite news|title=AG Andrew Dating Foodie |url=http://www.nypost.com/seven/12082008/gossip/pagesix/ag_andrew_dating_foodie_143139.htm |date=December 8, 2008 |work=New York Post |accessdate=2009-04-28 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090509151712/http://www.nypost.com/seven/12082008/gossip/pagesix/ag_andrew_dating_foodie_143139.htm |archivedate=May 9, 2009 }}</ref><ref>[https://www.nytimes.com/2010/05/15/nyregion/15sandralee.html?ref=nyregion \"A TV Cook\u2019s Next Serving? Cuomo Family Style\"] by Michael Barbaro, ''The New York Times'', May 15, 2010. \"Sandra Lee has built an empire with her simple cooking advice, and as Andrew M. Cuomo\u2019s companion, she may soon be hosting parties at the governor\u2019s mansion.\" Retrieved 2010-05-15.</ref>\n*Maria Cuomo Cole (born 1960) daughter of Matilda and Mario Cuomo, producer of social impact films at Cuomo Cole Productions, chairwoman of the charitable foundation Help USA, married to [[Kenneth Cole (designer)|Kenneth Cole]], a well-known New York fashion designer.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.chicagotribune.com/news/ct-xpm-1997-07-13-9707130085-story.html|title=A Lady First|last=Cohen|first=Paula|date=July 13, 1997|website=chicagotribune.com|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-05}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/08/12/fashion/weddings/emily-cole-matthew-dover.html|title=Emily Cole, Matthew Dover|date=2018-08-12|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-04-05|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>\n*Madeline Cuomo (born 1964) attorney, specializing in matrimonial law, graduate of Albany Law School.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Brady|first=Lois Smith|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1993/06/20/style/vows-madeline-cuomo-brian-o-donoghue.html|title=VOWS; Madeline Cuomo, Brian O'Donoghue|date=1993-06-20|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-04-05|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.businessinsider.com/meet-the-cuomo-family-andrew-mario-new-york-politics-2020-3|title=Meet the Cuomo family, the New York political dynasty that's become the face of America's response to the pandemic|last=Davis|first=Dominic-Madori|website=Business Insider|access-date=2020-04-05}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.oprahmag.com/entertainment/a31945095/mario-matilda-cuomo-love-story/|title=Andrew Cuomo's Mom and Dad Had an Incredible 60-Year Marriage|last=Janes|first=DeAnna|date=2020-03-27|website=Oprah Magazine|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-05}}</ref>\n*[[Chris Cuomo|Christopher Cuomo]] (born August 9, 1970), son of Mario and Matilda Cuomo; [[CNN]] Anchor; host of \"Cuomo Prime Time\" evening news program; Former [[ABC News]] chief law and justice correspondent; former news anchor for ''[[Good Morning America]]''; co-anchor for ABC's [[20/20 (US television series)|20/20]]; winner of six national [[Emmys]]; picked as one of ''[[People (magazine)|People]]'' magazine's \"50 Sexiest People\" in 1997.\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Cuomo family| ]]\n[[Category:American families of Italian ancestry]]\n[[Category:New York (state) Democrats]]\n[[Category:Political families of the United States]]\n[[Category:Roman Catholic families]]\n", "text_old": "{{about|the New York political family|other uses|Cuomo (disambiguation)}}\n[[File:Andrew_Cuomo_2014.jpg|250px|thumb|upright|[[Andrew Cuomo]], [[governor of New York]]]]\nThe '''Cuomo family''' ({{IPAc-en|\u02c8|k|w|o\u028a|m|o\u028a}} {{respell|KWOH|moh}}, {{IPA-it|\u02c8kw\u0254\u02d0mo|lang}}) is an [[United States|American]] [[political family]]. It includes [[Mario Cuomo|Mario]] and [[Matilda Cuomo]] (''n\u00e9e'' Raffa) and their five children: [[Margaret I. Cuomo|Margaret]], [[Andrew Cuomo|Andrew]], Maria, Madeline, and [[Chris Cuomo|Christopher]].  [[Mario Cuomo]] and his son [[Andrew Cuomo]] both have served as [[governor of New York]].\n\nMario Cuomo's parents, Andrea and Immacolata Cuomo, both [[immigration to the United States|immigrated to the United States]] from Italy; Andrea in 1926 and Immacolata in 1927.<ref>\"[https://www.nytimes.com/1995/04/25/obituaries/immaculata-cuomo-92-governor-s-mother.html Immaculata Cuomo, 92, Governor's Mother]\" (April 25, 1995), ''New York Times''.</ref>  Matilda Raffa Cuomo's parents both immigrated to the United State from Sicily; Carmelo \"Charles\" Raffa arrived in New York in 1927, and Mary ([[Birth name|n\u00e9e]] Gitto) Raffa in 1928.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1995/06/23/obituaries/mary-raffa-cuomo-s-mother-in-law-91.html|title=Mary Raffa; Cuomo's Mother-in-Law, 91|date=1995-06-23|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-03-30|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>\n\n*[[Mario Cuomo]] (June 15, 1932-January 1, 2015), unsuccessful candidate for [[Lieutenant Governor of New York]] (1974); appointed [[New York Secretary of State]] by Governor [[Hugh Carey]] (1975\u20131978); unsuccessful candidate in 1977 Democratic primary for [[mayor of New York City]] (lost to [[Ed Koch]]); unsuccessful [[Liberal Party of New York]] candidate in general election for mayor of New York City (1977), again losing to Ed Koch; Lieutenant Governor of New York 1979\u20131982; [[Governor of New York]] (1983\u20131994); keynote speaker at the [[1984 Democratic National Convention]] in [[San Francisco]].<ref>http://www.italian-american.com/mario-cu.htm</ref>\n*[[Matilda Cuomo]], (born September 16, 1931) former First Lady of New York (1983\u20131994); educator and lifelong advocate for women, children, and families; proponent of New York State Mentoring Program; founder of Mentoring USA nonprofit organization; inducted into [[National Women's Hall of Fame|National Women\u2019s Hall of Fame]] in 2017.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.timesunion.com/tuplus-local/article/Matilda-Cuomo-thrilled-by-National-Women-s-Hall-10926137.php|title=Matilda Cuomo thrilled by National Women's Hall of Fame induction|last=Grondahl|first=Paul|date=2017-02-12|website=Times Union|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-05}}</ref>\n*[[Margaret I. Cuomo|Margaret Cuomo]] (born March 29, 1955) daughter of Matilda and Mario Cuomo, is a noted physician and radiologist; author and champion of cancer prevention; co-founder of the Italian Language Foundation.\n*[[Andrew Cuomo]] (born December 6, 1957), son of Mario and Matilda Cuomo; [[United States Secretary of Housing and Urban Development]] (1997\u20132001); [[New York State Attorney General]] (2007\u20132010); [[governor of New York]] (2011\u2013present).<ref>{{cite news| url=http://findarticles.com/p/articles/mi_m1571/is_n11_V9/ai_13625807 | work=Insight on the News | first=Kenneth | last=Silber | title=New testing ground for the other Cuomo - Andrew Cuomo, son of New York State Governor Mario Cuomo | date=March 15, 1993}}</ref> From 1990 to 2003, Andrew Cuomo was married to [[Kerry Kennedy]], daughter of [[Robert F. Kennedy]] and [[Ethel Skakel]].<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20121023042328/http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P1-75020276.html HighBeam]</ref> After Cuomo and Kennedy divorced, Cuomo dated Food Network host [[Sandra Lee (cook)|Sandra Lee]] from 2005 until September 2019.<ref>{{cite news|title=AG Andrew Dating Foodie |url=http://www.nypost.com/seven/12082008/gossip/pagesix/ag_andrew_dating_foodie_143139.htm |date=December 8, 2008 |work=New York Post |accessdate=2009-04-28 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090509151712/http://www.nypost.com/seven/12082008/gossip/pagesix/ag_andrew_dating_foodie_143139.htm |archivedate=May 9, 2009 }}</ref><ref>[https://www.nytimes.com/2010/05/15/nyregion/15sandralee.html?ref=nyregion \"A TV Cook\u2019s Next Serving? Cuomo Family Style\"] by Michael Barbaro, ''The New York Times'', May 15, 2010. \"Sandra Lee has built an empire with her simple cooking advice, and as Andrew M. Cuomo\u2019s companion, she may soon be hosting parties at the governor\u2019s mansion.\" Retrieved 2010-05-15.</ref>\n*Maria Cuomo Cole (born 1960) daughter of Matilda and Mario Cuomo, producer of social impact films at Cuomo Cole Productions, chairwoman of the charitable foundation Help USA, married to [[Kenneth Cole (designer)|Kenneth Cole]], a well-known New York fashion designer.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.chicagotribune.com/news/ct-xpm-1997-07-13-9707130085-story.html|title=A Lady First|last=Cohen|first=Paula|date=July 13, 1997|website=chicagotribune.com|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-05}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/08/12/fashion/weddings/emily-cole-matthew-dover.html|title=Emily Cole, Matthew Dover|date=2018-08-12|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-04-05|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>\n*Madeline Cuomo (born 1964) attorney, specializing in matrimonial law, graduate of Albany Law School.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Brady|first=Lois Smith|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1993/06/20/style/vows-madeline-cuomo-brian-o-donoghue.html|title=VOWS; Madeline Cuomo, Brian O'Donoghue|date=1993-06-20|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-04-05|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.businessinsider.com/meet-the-cuomo-family-andrew-mario-new-york-politics-2020-3|title=Meet the Cuomo family, the New York political dynasty that's become the face of America's response to the pandemic|last=Davis|first=Dominic-Madori|website=Business Insider|access-date=2020-04-05}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.oprahmag.com/entertainment/a31945095/mario-matilda-cuomo-love-story/|title=Andrew Cuomo's Mom and Dad Had an Incredible 60-Year Marriage|last=Janes|first=DeAnna|date=2020-03-27|website=Oprah Magazine|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-05}}</ref>\n*[[Chris Cuomo|Christopher Cuomo]] (born August 9, 1970), son of Mario and Matilda Cuomo; [[CNN]] Anchor; host of \"Cuomo Prime Time\" evening news program; Former [[ABC News]] chief law and justice correspondent; former news anchor for ''[[Good Morning America]]''; co-anchor for ABC's [[20/20 (US television series)|20/20]]; winner of six national [[Emmys]]; picked as one of ''[[People (magazine)|People]]'' magazine's \"50 Sexiest People\" in 1997.\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Cuomo family| ]]\n[[Category:American families of Italian ancestry]]\n[[Category:New York (state) Democrats]]\n[[Category:Political families of the United States]]\n[[Category:Roman Catholic families]]\n", "name_user": "Jamesmcmahon0", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200etop:Typo fixing,typo(s) fixed: \u2019s \u2192 's", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cuomo_family"}
{"title_page": "2021 Copa Am\u00e9rica Group B", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2019}}\n'''Group B of the [[2021 Copa Am\u00e9rica]]''', also referred to as the '''North Zone''', will take place in June 2021 in Colombia. The group consists of hosts [[Colombia national football team|Colombia]], defending champions [[Brazil national football team|Brazil]], guests [[Qatar national football team|Qatar]], [[Venezuela national football team|Venezuela]], [[Ecuador national football team|Ecuador]] and [[Peru national football team|Peru]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://fcf.com.co/wp-content/uploads/2020/03/SCHEDULE-CA2020-v8-horarios-004.pdf |title=CONMEBOL Copa Am\u00e9rica 2020 schedule |website=[[Colombian Football Federation]] |format=PDF |date=4 March 2020 |access-date=5 March 2020 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200305010803/https://fcf.com.co/wp-content/uploads/2020/03/SCHEDULE-CA2020-v8-horarios-004.pdf |archive-date=5 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Teams==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Draw position\n! Team\n! data-sort-type=\"number\"| Appearance\n! Previous best<br />performance\n! [[FIFA World Rankings|FIFA Rankings]]<br />June 2021\n|-\n| B1 || style=white-space:nowrap | {{fb|COL}} (hosts) || 23rd || data-sort-value=\"1.3\" | '''Winners''' ([[2001 Copa Am\u00e9rica|2001]]) ||\n|-\n| B2 || style=white-space:nowrap | {{fb|BRA}} || 37th || data-sort-value=\"1.1\" | '''Winners''' ([[1919 South American Championship|1919]], [[1922 South American Championship|1922]], [[1949 South American Championship|1949]], [[1989 Copa Am\u00e9rica|1989]], [[1997 Copa Am\u00e9rica|1997]], [[1999 Copa Am\u00e9rica|1999]], [[2004 Copa Am\u00e9rica|2004]], [[2007 Copa Am\u00e9rica|2007]], [[2019 Copa Am\u00e9rica|2019]]) ||\n|-\n| B3 || style=white-space:nowrap | {{fb|QAT}} (invitee) || 2nd || data-sort-value=\"9\" | Group stage ([[2019 Copa Am\u00e9rica|2019]]) ||\n|-\n| B4 || style=white-space:nowrap | {{fb|VEN}} || 19th || data-sort-value=\"4.2\" | Fourth place ([[2011 Copa Am\u00e9rica|2011]]) ||\n|-\n| B5 || style=white-space:nowrap | {{fb|ECU}} || 29th || data-sort-value=\"4.1\" | Fourth place ([[1959 South American Championship (Ecuador)|1959 (E)]], [[1993 Copa Am\u00e9rica|1993]]) ||\n|-\n| B6 || style=white-space:nowrap | {{fb|PER}} || 33rd || data-sort-value=\"1.2\" | '''Winners''' ([[1939 South American Championship|1939]], [[1975 Copa Am\u00e9rica|1975]]) ||\n|}\n\n==Standings==\n{{2021 Copa Am\u00e9rica group tables|Group B}}\n\nIn the [[2021 Copa Am\u00e9rica knockout stage#Quarter-finals|quarter-finals]]:\n*The winners of Group B will advance to play the fourth-placed team of [[2021 Copa Am\u00e9rica Group A|Group A]].\n*The runners-up of Group B will advance to play the third-placed team of Group A.\n*The third-placed team of Group B will advance to play the runners-up of Group A.\n*The fourth-placed team of Group B will advance to play the winners of Group A.\n\n==Matches==\n{{Hatnote|All match times listed are local, [[Time in Colombia|COT]] ([[UTC\u221205:00|UTC\u22125]]).}}\n\n===Matchday 1===\n\n====Colombia vs Ecuador====\n<section begin=B01 />{{Football box\n|date       = {{Start date|2020|6|13|df=y}}\n|time       = 20:00 <includeonly>[[Time in Colombia|COT]]</includeonly>\n|team1      = {{fb-rt|COL}}\n|score      = {{score link|2021 Copa Am\u00e9rica Group B#Colombia vs Ecuador|Match 2}}\n|team2      = {{fb|ECU}}\n|goals1     =\n|goals2     =\n|stadium    = [[Estadio El Camp\u00edn]], [[Bogot\u00e1]]\n|attendance =\n|referee    =\n|report     =\n}}<section end=B01 />\n\n====Brazil vs Venezuela====\n<section begin=B02 />{{Football box\n|date       = {{Start date|2020|6|14|df=y}}\n|time       = 17:00 <includeonly>[[Time in Colombia|COT]]</includeonly>\n|team1      = {{fb-rt|BRA}}\n|score      = {{score link|2021 Copa Am\u00e9rica Group B#Brazil vs Venezuela|Match 5}}\n|team2      = {{fb|VEN}}\n|goals1     =\n|goals2     =\n|stadium    = [[Estadio Ol\u00edmpico Pascual Guerrero]], [[Cali]]\n|attendance =\n|referee    =\n|report     =\n}}<section end=B02 />\n\n====Peru vs Qatar====\n<section begin=B03 />{{Football box\n|date       = {{Start date|2020|6|14|df=y}}\n|time       = 20:00 <includeonly>[[Time in Colombia|COT]]</includeonly>\n|team1      = {{fb-rt|PER}}\n|score      = {{score link|2021 Copa Am\u00e9rica Group B#Peru vs Qatar|Match 6}}\n|team2      = {{fb|QAT}}\n|goals1     =\n|goals2     =\n|stadium    = [[Atanasio Girardot Sports Complex|Estadio Atanasio Girardot]], [[Medell\u00edn]]\n|attendance =\n|referee    =\n|report     =\n}}<section end=B03 />\n\n===Matchday 2===\n\n====Colombia vs Venezuela====\n<section begin=B04 />{{Football box\n|date       = {{Start date|2020|6|17|df=y}}\n|time       = 20:00 <includeonly>[[Time in Colombia|COT]]</includeonly>\n|team1      = {{fb-rt|COL}}\n|score      = {{score link|2021 Copa Am\u00e9rica Group B#Colombia vs Venezuela|Match 10}}\n|team2      = {{fb|VEN}}\n|goals1     =\n|goals2     =\n|stadium    = [[Estadio Ol\u00edmpico Pascual Guerrero]], [[Cali]]\n|attendance =\n|referee    =\n|report     =\n}}<section end=B04 />\n\n====Ecuador vs Qatar====\n<section begin=B05 />{{Football box\n|date       = {{Start date|2020|6|18|df=y}}\n|time       = 17:00 <includeonly>[[Time in Colombia|COT]]</includeonly>\n|team1      = {{fb-rt|ECU}}\n|score      = {{score link|2021 Copa Am\u00e9rica Group B#Ecuador vs Qatar|Match 11}}\n|team2      = {{fb|QAT}}\n|goals1     =\n|goals2     =\n|stadium    = [[Estadio El Camp\u00edn]], [[Bogot\u00e1]]\n|attendance =\n|referee    =\n|report     =\n}}<section end=B05 />\n\n====Peru vs Brazil====\n<section begin=B06 />{{Football box\n|date       = {{Start date|2020|6|18|df=y}}\n|time       = 20:00 <includeonly>[[Time in Colombia|COT]]</includeonly>\n|team1      = {{fb-rt|PER}}\n|score      = {{score link|2021 Copa Am\u00e9rica Group B#Peru vs Brazil|Match 12}}\n|team2      = {{fb|BRA}}\n|goals1     =\n|goals2     =\n|stadium    = [[Atanasio Girardot Sports Complex|Estadio At